6.","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant (the usual spelling in Scotland) of   Ramsey  . The Scottish Ramsays derive from Simund <i>de Ramesie</i>, recorded before 1175, who went to Scotland from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ramsey","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish (Antrim): habitational name from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire, now part of Cambridgeshire), from Old English <i>hramsa</i> ‘wild garlic’ + <i>ēg</i> ‘island, low-lying land’. Alternatively, the name may also arise from Ramsey (Essex), probably from the same etymology as the Huntingdonshire placename. However, this is unlikely to be the source of the Scottish surname. This form of the surname is also common in Ireland, where it is probably in most if not all cases an altered form of Scottish   Ramsay  ."]}]},{"name":"Marjory","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual modern spelling of   Margery .  It seems to have arisen as the result of folk etymological association of the name with that of the herb <i>marjoram</i> (  compare  Rosemary  ). This word is of uncertain origin; its Middle English and Old French form was <i>majorane</i>, without the first <i>-r-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marjory Ramsay of Auchterhouse was born about 1292, in Auchterhouse, Forfarshire, Scotland, her father, Robert Ramsay - First Laird of Auchterhouse, was 26 and her mother, Lady Ramsay, was 27. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Sir Patrick Ogilvie of Wester Powie. She died in 1357, in Forfarshire, Scotland, at the age of 66."},"et":{"about 1292–1357":"umbes 1292–1357","1292–1357":"1292–1357","1298–1365":"1298–1365","1300–1341":"1300–1341","1281–1329":"1281–1329","1319–1365":"1319–1365","1329–1365":"1329–1365","1359–Female":"1359–Surnud","1267–1350":"1267–1350","1267–Female":"1267–Surnud","about 1292":"umbes 1292","1341":"1341","1350":"1350","1292":"1292","1281":"1281","1359":"1359","